# Does Banning Guns Reduce Gun Violence? A Comprehensive Review

Gun violence remains a deeply contentious and polarizing issue in the United States and globally. The question of whether banning guns reduces gun violence has been debated extensively, with studies and reports offering varying conclusions. This report provides an in-depth, evidence-based analysis of the impact of gun bans and gun control laws on gun violence, drawing from a broad spectrum of research, including federal reviews, international studies, and academic analyses. The goal is to present a balanced, objective assessment grounded in the most reliable and recent data available.

---

## Overview of Gun Control and Violence Research

Gun control policies encompass a range of regulations, including bans on certain types of firearms, mandatory waiting periods, background checks, and restrictions on ownership by high-risk groups. The effectiveness of these measures in reducing firearm-related deaths—homicides, suicides, and accidental shootings—varies according to different studies and contexts.

### Federal Review Findings

A 2003 sweeping federal review by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) found no conclusive proof that gun control laws such as mandatory waiting periods or bans on certain weapons reduce firearm violence. The task force noted that many studies were inconsistent, narrow in scope, or methodologically flawed. For example, studies on firearm bans and ammunition bans showed mixed results, with some indicating decreases in violence and others showing increases. Problems such as exemptions for existing gun owners and increased firearm sales before bans complicated assessments. Similarly, studies on background checks were inconsistent, partly because denials of firearm purchase applications did not always prevent acquisition through other means ([CDC Review, 2003](https://www.cbsnews.com/news/no-proof-gun-laws-reduce-violence/)).

### Academic and International Perspectives

Contrasting with the CDC's cautious stance, a 2016 international study published in *Epidemiologic Reviews* analyzed gun laws and gun violence across multiple countries. This study found a compelling trend: the simultaneous implementation of multiple firearm restrictions—such as bans on powerful weapons, background checks, and licensing requirements—was associated with reductions in firearm deaths. The study emphasized that broad packages of gun laws, rather than isolated measures, tend to be effective. For instance, laws restricting purchase and access to firearms correlated with lower rates of intimate partner homicides and accidental child deaths ([Santaella-Tenorio et al., 2016](https://www.vox.com/2016/2/29/11120184/gun-control-study-international-evidence)).

### Contradictory Findings from Harvard Journal of Law & Public Policy

A controversial 2007 paper by criminologists Don B. Kates and Gary Mauser, published in the *Harvard Journal of Law & Public Policy*, argued that banning firearms would increase crime rather than reduce it. They claimed that more guns in private hands correlated with less crime, citing international comparisons and historical data. Their conclusion was that stringent gun controls did not correlate with reductions in criminal violence or suicide, and that anti-gun legislation might have the opposite effect ([Kates & Mauser, 2007](https://blog.gunassociation.org/banning-guns-will-increase-crime-harvard-study-overview/)).

However, this paper has been criticized for methodological flaws, lack of peer review, and selective use of data. The Harvard Injury Control Research Center and other experts have described it as a polemic rather than a scientific article, noting that it ignored much of the broader scientific literature on the subject ([Hemenway, 2009](https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/harvard-flaw-review/)).

